To pass on therefore towards his death, as the fittest transition unto his buriall; I am enabled to say of him, (by such as were eye and ear witnesses,) that he abundantly injoyed [that 
                  〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
               ] that happy calmness of death, which the Emperour Augustus was wont to pray for. I say he injoy'd it in both acceptions of the word. For first however he was sick of a burning Feaver, (which carried him up like Elias in a fiery Chariot) yet he had this rare happiness which is the priviledge of a few, that he even injoyed his whole disease without the least taint of deliration. That knot of union betwixt his body and his soul, was not violently broken, but very leasurely untyed; they having parted like two friends, not by a rude falling-out, but a loving farewell. Thus was his Euthanasia in the first acception of the word. But he had it much more, as to the second. For
